Creating Images with R

07/03/2023

My Meme

Here is a meme I made using R for this project. It is inspired by me and my friends experience with uni so far and in particular my poor ability to manage time resulting in many late nights relying on caffeine to be able to successfully make deadlines before going to class the next day with barely any sleep if any. This meme in itself is not massively original but it is my original take on the classic is this a pigeon meme

Below is the code used to generate the above meme in R

library(magick)

# meme source = https://www.google.com/url?sa=i&url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.vox.com%2F2018%2F5%2F15%2F17351806%2Fis-this-a-pigeon-anime-butterfly-meme-explained&psig=AOvVaw2SNkEw3HxGLc5uBiA4Cbl7&ust=1678238098227000&source=images&cd=vfe&ved=0CBEQjhxqFwoTCKj7-6TSyP0CFQAAAAAdAAAAABAD
#Load Base Image
baseMeme <- image_read("Confused Anime Guy.jpg") %>%
  image_scale("700x525")

#Make Top Text
topText <- image_blank(700, 80, color="black") %>%
  image_annotate("Uni Students Be Like:", color = "white", size = 70, gravity = "center")


#Annotate Base Meme into New image
AnnotatedBase <- image_annotate(baseMeme, "Student", color = "white", size = 50, location= "+150+120") %>%
  image_annotate("an adequate replacement for sleep",color = "white",boxcolor = 'black', size = 20, location= "+330+475") %>%
  image_annotate("Caffeine", color = "black",boxcolor = 'yellow', size = 35, location= "+480+100")


#Generate meme output by appending a vector array of the annotated image and top text
outputMeme <- image_append(c(topText, AnnotatedBase), stack = TRUE)


#print(outputMeme) #<- Artifact from testing
image_write(outputMeme, "scriptedMeme.png") #exports the final output

My GIF

Here is a GIF i made in R for this project. My motivation behind it is its inspired by the loss memes that originated from a Control Alt Delete comic that were real popular a couple years ago and I figured it would be cool to make without importing any source images at all and instead making the entire GIF using pure code.

Below is the code used to generate the above GIF in R

library(magick)

#frame size data
fWidth <- 700
fHeight <- 700


#Generating frame data
#Very unoriginal Loss meme from scratch because I spend too much time on the internet
frame1 <- image_blank(width = fWidth, height = fHeight, color = "black") %>%
  image_annotate("              ", location = "+200+150", size = 90, boxcolor = "red", degrees = 90) # Don't actually know how to make boxes could use more image blanks but this is quicker anyway

frame2 <- image_blank(width = fWidth, height = fHeight, color = "black") %>%
  image_annotate("              ", location = "+200+150", size = 90, boxcolor = "red", degrees = 90) %>%
  image_annotate("          ", location = "+500+250", size = 90, boxcolor = "red", degrees = 90)

frame3 <- image_blank(width = fWidth, height = fHeight, color = "black") %>%
  image_annotate("              ", location = "+200+150", size = 90, boxcolor = "red", degrees = 90) %>%
  image_annotate("              ", location = "+500+150", size = 90, boxcolor = "red", degrees = 90)

frame4 <- image_blank(width = fWidth, height = fHeight, color = "black") %>%
  image_annotate("              ", location = "+200+150", size = 90, boxcolor = "red", degrees = 90) %>%
  image_annotate("              ", location = "+280+380", size = 90, boxcolor = "red")

frameVector = c(frame1, frame2, frame3, frame4) # satisfying the requirement of vector use


#generating the top text as an image
topText <- image_blank(fWidth, 80, color="white") %>%
  image_annotate("Is this Loss?", color = "black", size = 70, gravity = "center")

#using a loop to append the top text to each frame.
for (i in 1:length(frameVector)) {
  frameVector[i] <- image_append(c(topText, frameVector[i]), stack = TRUE)
}


image_animate(frameVector, fps = 0.5) %>% image_write("loss.gif") #output the final result
